  "prompt": "How is bail amount calculated in Indian courts?",
  "response": "In Indian courts, bail amount calculation involves several factors:\n\n1. Legal Basis\n- Depends on Criminal Procedure Code (CrPC)\n- Magistrates and Sessions Courts have bail-setting powers\n\n2. Determining Factors\n- Nature and severity of the alleged crime\n- Accused's criminal history\n- Flight risk potential\n- Economic background of the accused\n- Likelihood of tampering with evidence\n- Social status and reputation\n\n3. Calculation Methods\n- No standardized formula\n- Judge's discretionary power\n- Typically ranges from \u20b95,000 to several lakhs\n- Can be personal bond or cash deposit\n\n4. Types of Bail\n- Regular bail\n- Anticipatory bail\n- Interim bail\n\n5. Additional Considerations\n- Gravity of charges\n- Potential threat to society\n- Probability of conviction\n- Accused's cooperation during investigation\n\n6. Influencing Elements\n- Criminal record\n- Family background\n- Employment status\n- Community standing\n\n7. Special Provisions\n- Different considerations for serious offenses\n- Terrorist acts\n- Economic crimes\n- Sexual offenses\n\nThe bail amount is ultimately determined by the presiding judicial officer based on case-specific circumstances.",
